04382nam a22007815i 9780823254231DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232542317 a10.1515/97808232542312doi  a(DE-B1597)555064  a(OCoLC)861559244  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aD13b.C5838 2014 7aPHI0000002bisacsh04a907.22231 aClift, Sarah, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCommitting the Future to Memory :bHistory, Experience, Trauma /cSarah Clift. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (264 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Narrative Life Span, in the Wake: Benjamin and Arendt -- t2. Memory in Theory: The Childhood Memories of John Locke (Persons, Parrots) -- t3. Mourning Memory: The “End” of Art or, Reading (in) the Spirit of Hegel -- t4. Speculating on the Past, the Impact of the Present: Hegel and His Time(s) -- t5. In Lieu of a Last Word: Maurice Blanchot and the Future of Memory (Today) -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhereas historical determinacy conceives the past as a complex and unstable network of causalities, this book asks how history can be related to a more radical future. To pose that question, it does not reject determinacy outright but rather seeks to explore how it works. In examining what it means to be “determined” by history, it also asks what kind of openings there might be in our encounters with history for interruptions, re-readings, and re-writings.Engaging texts spanning multiple genres and several centuries—from John Locke to Maurice Blanchot, from Hegel to Benjamin—Clift looks at experiences of time that exceed the historical narration of experiences said to have occurred in time. She focuses on the co-existence of multiple temporalities and opens up the quintessentially modern notion of historical succession to other possibilities. The alternatives she draws out include the mediations of language and narration, temporal leaps, oscillations and blockages, and the role played by contingency in representation. She argues that such alternatives compel us to reassess the ways we understand history and identity in a traumatic, or indeed in a post-traumatic, age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCivilization, ModernxPhilosophy. 0aHistoriographyxPhilosophy. 7aPHILOSOPHY / General.2bisacsh  aEmpiricism.  aG. W. F. Hegel.  aHannah Arendt.  aMaurice Blanchot.  aMemory.  aSubjectivity.  aTemporality.  aTrauma.  aWalter Benjamin.  ahistory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823254231zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823254231423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823254231/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK